"# Chapter 5 — Atari 800 — POKEY, ANTIC, sprites

The Atari 800. Released November 1979. Priced at \\$1,000 at launch,
which was expensive. Designed by a team including Jay Miner (who
would later design the Amiga), Joe Decuir, and colleagues at Atari.

The Atari 8-bit family (400, 800, and later XL and XE machines) was
technically more advanced than most contemporaries. It didn't sell as
well as the Commodore 64 did later, but the people who used it tended
to love it.

## The processor

Same MOS 6502 as the C64 (specifically a 6502B in most Atari 8-bit
machines). Clock speed on the Atari 800: about 1.79 MHz on NTSC —
faster than the C64. Same 64K address space, same 8-bit shape.

The processor is the least interesting part of the Atari story. The
interesting part is the custom chips supporting it.

## The custom chips

Atari 8-bit machines have four famous custom chips:

- **ANTIC**: the graphics microcontroller. ANTIC is not just a video
  chip — it's an actual programmable coprocessor with its own
  instruction set for describing display lists. You write a display
  list in memory saying 'draw this many lines in this graphics mode,
  then this many lines in that mode,' and ANTIC follows it while
  the 6502 does other things. This is exceptional for 1979.

- **GTIA** (Graphics Television Interface Adapter): takes ANTIC's
  output and turns it into the actual color signals for the TV.
  Handles the palette (256 colors), players and missiles (hardware
  sprites), collision detection.

- **POKEY** (POtentiometer and KEYboard controller): handles sound,
  keyboard scanning, and serial I/O. POKEY has four voices, each a
  square-wave oscillator with a shift-register noise mode. It's not
  as musical as the C64's SID but it's characterful and legendary
  in its own right.

- **PIA** (Peripheral Interface Adapter, MOS 6520): controller
  ports.

The overall architecture — a modest 6502 supported by specialized
custom chips — is similar to the C64's, but the Atari version was
built two to three years earlier and is generally considered more
elegant. Jay Miner was a designer with taste.

## Display lists

The ANTIC's display list is worth pausing on. Because ANTIC runs its
own program (the display list) while the 6502 runs its program, an
Atari programmer can do things like: 'top of screen is high-res
text, middle is 320x192 graphics, bottom is another band of text.'
You write a small display list and ANTIC handles the whole switch
between modes for you, every frame.

Display lists are one of the earliest examples of a graphics
coprocessor with its own instruction stream. The idea would show up
again on the Amiga (the Copper), on early GPUs, and today in modern
graphics hardware (in a much more sophisticated form).

The idea in its essence: don't burn CPU cycles telling the graphics
hardware what to do every scan line. Give the graphics hardware a
program of its own.

## Players and missiles

Atari 8-bit sprites are called 'players' and 'missiles.' The GTIA
provides four 8-pixel-wide players and four 2-pixel-wide missiles,
which can be positioned independently on the screen and detect
collisions with each other and with the playfield.

Sprites — small movable images overlaid on a background — were a
big innovation. They let games have moving characters without the
CPU having to redraw them every frame. The Atari 2600 (the game
console) had two sprites. The 8-bit family has four plus four. The
C64 (a bit later) has eight. The Amiga would have hundreds if you
counted the sprite system creatively.

Motoi Scheme has a sprite module that captures this idea in software:

```
(sprite/make :id 'player-1
             :sheet 'characters
             :frame 0
             :x 160 :y 100
             :flip #f)

(sprite/move! 'player-1 :dx 2)

(sprite/collides? 'player-1 'enemy-1)
```

You can hear the Atari heritage in the vocabulary.

## POKEY

The POKEY sound chip has four channels. Each channel is a shift
register that clocks at a programmable rate, producing tones. There
are also several noise-generation modes for percussion and effects.
Two adjacent channels can be combined for 16-bit frequency resolution
and cleaner tones.

Not as many voices as SID, no filter or ring modulation, but POKEY
has a sound of its own. Games like *M.U.L.E.* and *Ballblazer* used
POKEY well. The sound is direct, bright, and has a specific character
you can recognize a decade later.

Motoi's sound module borrows the same shape: four voices, each with
a waveform, a frequency, a volume. Same simple model, running in
software.

## What Motoi owes the Atari 800

The idea that custom chips can carry weight the CPU can't. The
display-list approach — hardware that runs its own tiny program in
parallel with the main CPU — shows up in Motoi's runtime as the
scheduler that runs cart display verbs alongside the language model.

Also: taste. The Atari 800 is a machine designed with taste. It does
things elegantly that other machines do awkwardly. Motoi's small
kernel and clean verb-set try to have some of the same quality.

## A tiny example

Simulating an ANTIC-style display list in Motoi Scheme. The display
list is a data structure; a renderer walks it:

```
(define display-list
  '((mode text-40  :lines 4  :chars \"HIGH SCORE: 8420\")
    (mode graphics-8 :lines 100)
    (mode text-40  :lines 4  :chars \"PLAYER 1\")
    (mode graphics-9 :lines 92)
    (mode text-40  :lines 4  :chars \"LIVES: 3\")))

(define (render-display-list dl)
  (for-each
    (lambda (entry)
      (case (cadr entry)
        ((text-40)     (draw-text-band entry))
        ((graphics-8)  (draw-hires-band entry))
        ((graphics-9)  (draw-color-band entry))))
    dl))

;; ANTIC runs a display list like this every screen refresh, 60 times
;; a second, in parallel with whatever the 6502 is doing. Motoi's
;; scheduler works the same way, in software.
```

That's the shape of ANTIC-style graphics. Each mode is a small
instruction. The renderer follows the list. The CPU runs elsewhere.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Elegant hardware makes elegant software possible. The Atari's custom
chips took work off the CPU and let programmers focus on what they
wanted to say instead of how to say it in silicon. That is the same
move Motoi tries to make in software — small kernel, do the right
thing by default, let the programmer point at intent.

Jay Miner's fingerprint is on this machine and on the Amiga three
chapters from now. Watch for it. Some designers have a shape you can
recognize across decades.")
